      <hedline>
        <hl1>Jerusalem's Future: A Capital of Peace</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Harmon G Lewis letter on Karen Armstrong's July 16 article suggests central core of Old Jerusalem be made international city under United Nations jurisdiction</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No One People Owns Jerusalem,'' by Karen Armstrong (Op-Ed, July 16):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''No One People Owns Jerusalem,'' by Karen Armstrong (Op-Ed, July 16):</p>
        <p>One of the major points of contention between the Palestinians and the Israelis, as Ms. Armstrong suggests,  concerns the status of Jerusalem. Both sides claim it, or parts of it, as their capital.</p>
        <p>I would like to suggest a possible solution: that the central core of Old Jerusalem be made an international city under the jurisdiction of the United Nations.</p>
        <p>A Jerusalem under the United Nations would be a center open to all -- of peace, hope and spirituality for the region and for all humanity.</p>
        <p>HARMON G. LEWIS  New London, N.H., July 17, 2000</p>
      </block>
